`IFormFile` buffers the entire request into memory by default — that's why it OOMs. Instead, read the raw `HttpRequest.Body` stream (or use `MultipartReader`) and write chunks directly to disk.

**Minimal API approach using `MultipartReader`:**

```csharp
app.MapPost("/upload", async (HttpRequest request) =>
{
    var boundary = request.GetMultipartBoundary()
        ?? throw new BadHttpRequestException("Not a multipart request");

    var reader = new MultipartReader(boundary, request.Body);
    var section = await reader.ReadNextSectionAsync();

    while (section is not null)
    {
        if (ContentDispositionHeaderValue.TryParse(
                section.ContentDisposition, out var cd) && cd.IsFileDisposition())
        {
            var destPath = Path.Combine("/tmp/uploads",
                Path.GetRandomFileName());

            await using var fs = File.Create(destPath);
            await section.Body.CopyToAsync(fs);   // streams in chunks, ~80 KB default
        }
        section = await reader.ReadNextSectionAsync();
    }

    return Results.Ok("Uploaded");
})
.DisableAntiforgery();
```

**Required Kestrel configuration** (defaults cap at ~30 MB):

```csharp
builder.WebHost.ConfigureKestrel(k =>
{
    k.Limits.MaxRequestBodySize = 2L * 1024 * 1024 * 1024; // 2 GB
});
```

Also disable form buffering limits so the framework doesn't try to buffer:

```csharp
builder.Services.Configure<FormOptions>(o =>
{
    o.MultipartBodyLengthLimit = 2L * 1024 * 1024 * 1024;
});
```

**Key points:**

| | `IFormFile` | `MultipartReader` |
|---|---|---|
| Memory | Buffers entire file | Streams in small chunks |
| 2 GB file | OOM crash | ~80 KB resident |
| Binding | Model-bound | Manual parsing |

**Why this works:** `MultipartReader` reads the multipart MIME body section-by-section without materializing the file into memory. `CopyToAsync` streams 80 KB chunks from the request socket straight to the `FileStream`.

> **Tip:** For production, add a `CancellationToken`, validate the file name/content-type before writing, and consider streaming to a temp file then renaming — this avoids partial files on aborted uploads.
